    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Development of Improved Methods for the Stabilization of 2-D NSHP Recursive Digital</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Santhi S. Kumaran</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Stabilization<br />Recursive Digital</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Aug-2009 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0064</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Digital filtering occupies an important place in the field of digital signal and image processing. The 2-D
recursive digital filters have potential use in many applications due to their advantages of less storage and
computation time compared to the non recursive digital filters. But the stability problem associated with
the recursive filters has upto now impeded the progress in the application of the same. Stability is an
important property that must be considered in any practical application of a system. Unstable systems
usually exhibit erratic and extreme behavior and cause overflow in any practical implementation.
In the design of2-D recursive digital filters, it is difficult to ensure their stability in the beginning stage of
the design since it is computationally tedious to take care of the stability constraints during the
approximation stage. So it would be advantageous to device a technique by which stability problem could
be detached from the approximation problem, and it is here that stabilization methods come into play.
Thus, at the end of approximation process, if the filter becomes unstable, stabilization procedures are used
to stabilize an unstable filter without disturbing its frequency response.
Most of the research contributions made so for on the Stabilization of 2-D recursive filters were focused
on 2-D Quarter Plane (QP) filters and not on 2-D Non-Symmetric Half Plane (NSHP) filters except a few..
The earlier work on the stabilization of NSHP filters using Planar Least Squares Inverse (PLSI) method
does not lead to an always stable system. Moreover stabilization ofNSHP filters are generally carried out
by mapping techniques. to convert NSHP to QP filter. This research aims at developing improved
stabilization procedures for NSHP fUters.
This thesis presents two stabilization methods developed in this research. The first approach is based on
the PLS[ method using a new way of form preserving transformation. [n this method of stabilizing 2D
NSHP recursive filters, the new way of form-preserving transformation is used to convert the 20 NSHP
polynomial into 10 and, then, obtain the ID LSI of the form-preserving 10 polynomial. The emphasis
here is that, the presented transformation when applied to NSHP would always lead to optimal LS[ (i.e.no
missing powers of z) and hence the stability is guaranteed. LSI polynomial is minimum phase and this
implies that the filter represented by LSI polynomial is stable. The PLSI can then be formed from 10 LSI.
In the second approach we extend the concept of reciprocity and apply it directly without any mapping
techniques to stabilize 2D NSHP filters which are unstable when all the singularities lie within the unit
bicircle. The characteristic of the original filter is preserved after stabilization through this approach.
Apart from the stabilization approaches, a stability testing method using Lagrange constrained
optimization approach is also proposed.
In our opinion, the methods developed will be of great help to the 2-D recursive filter designers to ensure
stability of the filters. The contributions were published in refereed journals.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9395">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9395</a></td></tr>
